projectScope.summary:
The Proponent is proposing a heli-supported quartz mineral exploration program on the Astro Property located approximately 193 km and 207 km northeast of Ross River and Faro, respectively. The property is a transboundary property with the majority of the property in NWT. In the Yukon, the property is located within the Traditional Territories of the Ross River Dena Council, Liard First Nation, and the First Nation of Na-Cho Nyak Dun.&nbsp;
The Yukon portion of the property consists of 400 claims, but much of the drilling will occur on 40 claims. Prospecting and soil and rock sampling will occur over the 400 claims. The exploration program consists mainly of a diamond drilling program with a primary focus in two areas (HIT and SER). The proposed drilling is in the alpine, above treeline, in steep rocky mountainous terrain. Soil, rock, and sediment sampling; geological mapping; and prospecting will also occur.
Access to the property and work areas is via helicopter from an existing camp in the NWT located approximately 12-20 km from the areas of interest at the 222 airstrip near the end of the North Canol Road. Additionally, the Noth Canol Road is used to access the camp (about two trips per week). Exploration activities will occur annually from May 15 to October 15 for 10 years.

The Project involves timber harvesting of up to 14 963 m3 of timber resources for provision of forest resources (sawlogs and fuel wood for local markets) and reduction of wildfire risk through fuel reduction and stand conversion. Project activities will occur within the boundary of the Lubbock Valley Timber Harvest Plan (DRAFT 2024) area. The Project falls within the Territory of the Carcross/Tagish First Nation. Project activities include the use of existing access roads that overlap with Settlement Land parcels CTFN R-19B and CTFN R-26B.&nbsp;
Timber harvesting and associated activities are proposed to occur year-round for a 10-year period ending in April 2034. Harvesting activities are planned to occur during periods of the year when the ground is frozen and there is a minimum of 20 cm snow depth in Operating Unit 1 and Operating Unit 2, as well as during snow-free seasons in Operating Unit 2. If natural regeneration does not meet reforestation stocking standards, silviculture activities may occur for an additional 10-year period after harvesting is complete.&nbsp;
Note: The Designated Office received clarification from the Proponent that no proposed project activities, including access to the THP, overlap with Carcross/Tagish First Nation (CTFN) Settlement Land. As such, CTFN has been removed from the YESAB Online Registry as an identified Decision Body. See Project Note YOR 2024-0118-0034 for more information.

