projectScope.summary:
The Summary was updated on October 17, 2025 - changes are in BOLD
The Project consists of fuel abatement to reduce wildfire risk to nearby residences and the City of Whitehorse and for the provision of forest resources (sawlogs and fuel wood). The Project is located within the municipal boundary of the City of Whitehorse, immediately to the west of the Whitehorse Copper and Wolf Creek subdivisions and accessed by the existing Copper Haul/Mount Sima Road that originates at km 1415 of the Alaska Highway. The Project overlaps with the Territories of the Kwanlin Dün First Nation and the Ta’an Kwäch’än Council.&nbsp;
Processing of firewood, when occurring within central processing areas, could occur during any period of the year. Harvesting activities and road construction activities will occur seasonally between October 1 and spring thaw (usually around April 15), and road construction activities might also occur between spring thaw and October 1 if fire danger is low, for a 10-year period.&nbsp;

The Project is the proposed fuel abatement clearing and release of an 11-ha land parcel within the 311 ha McGowan lands Agricultural Reserve 2004-0433. The land will be released for the purpose of non-soil based arable agriculture. Three 2 ha areas and one 3.2 ha area will be leased to successful applicants.
This Project is located at km 151 of the South Klondike Highway, approximately 28 km South of Whitehorse, and will be accessed by Mosquito Road. The Project is within the Kwanlin Dün First Nation Territory.
Development of the parcels will be completed by the successful applicants and may occur between April 15 and November 30. The project is assessed based on a 30-year lease length maximum as per the Lands Act; activity duration is dependent on sublease duration.&nbsp;

