projectScope.summary:
The Proponent is proposing a ground-based and heli-supported quartz exploration program on 92 claims at the Nidd Property, at Macmillan Pass, near the Yukon/NWT border in southeast Yukon. The Project is located approximately 200 km northeast of Ross River off the North Canol Road and is within the Territories of the Ross River Dena Council, the Liard First Nation, and the First Nation of Na-Cho Nyäk Dun.&nbsp;
Ground-based access to the Nidd Project will be via the Valley Road located at km 441.8 of the North Canol Road. Additionally, air access will be provided by fixed wing aircraft to the Macmillan Pass Airstrip and by helicopter from the Tom Camp located east of the Nidd Property.&nbsp;
Project activities include the re-establishment of the Valley Road to allow for ground-based exploration and access for vehicles as large as fuel tanker trucks. Activities are scheduled to occur annually from May 1 to October 31, for 10 years.&nbsp;
The Valley Road
The Valley Road is approximately 21 km long, beginning at the North Canol Road and ending near Boundary Creek on the Nidd claims. The first 6.679 km of the road is permitted under a separate Mining Land Use Approval and the last 14.334 km is on the Nidd claims. The entire length of the road is on the Proponent’s claims.&nbsp;
The first 0.927 km of road is already established. The next 5.752 km of the road moving west is located on the Jason claims (also owed by the Proponent) and this portion is proposed to be re-established as a part of this assessment (this is referred to by the Proponent as Stage 3 in the proposal documents).
The 14.334 km of road on the Nidd claims is also proposed to be re-established as part of this assessment (this is referred to by the Proponent as Stage 4 in the proposal documents).&nbsp;
The Proponent is proposing to delist the Valley Road, an unmaintained highway under the Highways Act, through an order of the Commissioner in Executive Council (i.e. an Order in Council), which would turn the Valley Road into a private road. If an Order in Council is approved, it will allow the Proponent to rehabilitate, maintain, and reclaim the Valley Road as a private road permitted under the Quartz Mining Act as considered in this assessment.  Access to the Valley Road is controlled via the gate at the Jason Bridge.

